┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ PHASE 1 — LEGENDRE-CATTANEO SIEVE (20:46:14 → 03:37:17)                       │
│ Duration: ~6h 51m 3s                                                           │
│                                                                                 │
│ PURPOSE:                                                                        │
│ Enumerate all prime-power components (p, 2e) where σ(p^{2e}) has ALL prime     │
│ factors ≡ 1 or 3 (mod 8).  This is the Legendre-Cattaneo obstruction:          │
│                                                                                 │
│   Theorem (Cattaneo 1951 / Hagis 1980):                                        │
│   If N is quasiperfect, then 2N + 1 ≡ 1 (mod 8), so σ(N) = 2N + 1 ≡ 1 (mod 8)│
│   Since σ is multiplicative and N = ∏ p_i^{2e_i}, each σ(p_i^{2e_i})          │
│   must have ALL prime factors q satisfying q ≡ 1 or 3 (mod 8).                │
│   Any factor q ≡ 5 or 7 (mod 8) invalidates the component.                    │
│                                                                                 │
│ ALGORITHM (Two-Pass Cyclotomic Screening):                                      │
│                                                                                 │
│   For each odd prime p ≤ 250,000 and each even exponent 2e ∈ {2, 4}:          │
│                                                                                 │
│   Step 1 — Compute σ(p^{2e}) via pure Rust:                                    │
│     σ(p^{2e}) = (p^{2e+1} - 1) / (p - 1)                                      │
│     Using u128 arithmetic (no FFI overhead).                                    │
│                                                                                 │
│   Step 2 — Cyclotomic decomposition:                                            │
│     σ(p^{2e}) = ∏_{d | (2e+1)} Φ_d(p)                                         │
│     where Φ_d(p) is the d-th cyclotomic polynomial evaluated at p.             │
│     This factors the large σ value into smaller cyclotomic factors              │
│     that are much faster to trial-divide.                                       │
│                                                                                 │
│   Step 3 — Trial division with early exit:                                      │
│     For each cyclotomic factor Φ_d(p):                                          │
│       a) Trial-divide by all 664,579 primes up to 10^7                         │
│       b) CHECK MOD 8: if any extracted factor q ≡ 5 or 7 (mod 8) → REJECT     │
│       c) If a large composite cofactor remains:                                 │
│          - If cofactor ≡ 5 or 7 (mod 8) → REJECT (subgroup closure property)  │
│          - If cofactor ≡ 1 or 3 (mod 8) and composite → Pollard ρ fallback    │
│          - If prime (Miller-Rabin, 15 witnesses) → check mod 8 directly        │
│                                                                                 │
│ MATHEMATICAL NOTE on mod-8 subgroup closure:                                    │
│   The set {1, 3} is closed under multiplication mod 8:                          │
│     1×1=1, 1×3=3, 3×3=9≡1 (mod 8)                                             │
│   Therefore, if a composite number ≡ 5 or 7 (mod 8), it MUST contain at       │
│   least one prime factor ≡ 5 or 7 (mod 8), so we can reject immediately       │
│   without factoring.  But 5×7=35≡3 (mod 8) means a residue of 1 or 3          │
│   could still hide bad factors — those need full factorization.                │
│                                                                                 │
│ PARALLELISM:                                                                    │
│   Rayon parallel iterator over all primes.  Each worker thread:                │
│   • Maintains a local component buffer and sigma cache                          │
│   • Accumulates timing diagnostics via AtomicU64                               │
│   • Reports progress every 500 primes via PROGRESS|UPDATE messages             │
│   • Flushes sigma cache into shared Mutex<SigmaCache> after completion         │
│                                                                                 │
│ OUTPUT:                                                                         │
│   Components that survive the sieve form the input to Phase 2.                  │
│   They are sorted by abundance ratio σ(p^{2e})/p^{2e} in descending order     │
│   (small primes have the highest ratios, enabling aggressive early pruning).   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

