┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ PRE-PHASE 2 — Precomputation (03:37:17 → 03:37:19)                             │
│                                                                                 │
│ 1. Suffix Abundance Array                                                       │
│    For DFS pruning, precompute suffix_abundance[i] = max product of ≤7          │
│    abundance ratios available from component index i onward.                    │
│    Since components are sorted by ratio descending, the best-k from [i..]       │
│    are the first k entries.  This enables O(1) "can we still reach σ/N ≥ 2?"   │
│    checks at every DFS node (Abundance Pruning A1).                            │
│                                                                                 │
│ 2. Illegal Z-Valuations                                                         │
│    Precompute (p^e, p^{e+1}) tuples for primes p ≤ 250 and exponents ≤ 4       │
│    where σ(p^{2e}) ≡ 5 or 7 (mod 8).  Used by ray-casting to instantly reject  │
│    candidate z values with forbidden p-adic valuations.                          │
│                                                                                 │
│ 3. Z3 CDCL Pruner Initialization                                               │
│    Creates crossbeam MPMC channel for broadcasting learned conflict clauses     │
│    across all Rayon worker threads.  Two trap types:                            │
│    • Starvation traps: prefix structurally cannot reach abundance ≥ 2           │
│    • Zsigmondy traps: σ factors violate mod-8 obstruction                      │
│    Conflict clauses are stored in a RwLock<Vec> for parallel read access.       │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

[2026-03-28 03:37:17] Z3 CDCL pruner initialized. Conflict learning active.


┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ PHASE 2 — FUSED DFS CONSTRUCTION & RAY-CASTING (03:37:17 → 03:37:19)          │
│ Duration: ~2 seconds                                                           │
│                                                                                 │
│ PURPOSE:                                                                        │
│ Construct all feasible N_L = ∏ p_i^{2e_i} prefixes via depth-first search,     │
│ applying multiple layers of pruning at each node.  When a prefix exceeds       │
│ the stopping threshold (N_L > 10^11), immediately perform exact ray-casting    │
│ to test whether any valid N_R completion exists.                               │
│                                                                                 │
│ DFS STRUCTURE:                                                                  │
│   • 9,172 components form the children at each DFS level                       │
│   • Each node selects a subset of components (distinct primes only)             │
│   • children[i] is only eligible if its prime p_i > all primes already used    │
│     (components are sorted, so last_idx enforces monotonicity)                  │
│                                                                                 │
│ PARALLELISM:                                                                    │
│   • Depth < 2: Rayon parallel work-stealing (clone prefix for each child)      │
│   • Depth ≥ 2: Sequential push/pop recursion (zero allocation)                 │
│   • Lock-free AtomicU64 slots (64 total) for active-prime telemetry            │
│                                                                                 │
│ PRUNING LAYERS (in order of application at each DFS node):                     │
│                                                                                 │
│   1. BOUND CHECK: N_L > 10^37 → prune (exceeds search range)                  │
│                                                                                 │
│   2. Z3 CDCL CONFLICT CHECK (ENG-202):                                         │
│      If any previously learned conflict clause's primes are a subset of        │
│      the current prefix's primes, the prefix is structurally doomed.            │
│      • RwLock allows 100% parallel reads across all Rayon workers              │
│      • Short-circuit: skip entirely when no conflicts learned yet              │
│      • MPMC channel broadcasts new conflicts to sibling threads in real-time   │
│                                                                                 │
│   3. ZSIGMONDY TRAP DETECTION:                                                 │
│      Check if any accumulated σ factor in the prefix ≡ 5 or 7 (mod 8).         │
│      If so, learn a new conflict clause and broadcast via Z3 CDCL channel.     │
│                                                                                 │
│   4. LLL LATTICE DIOPHANTINE PRUNING (ENG-203, Wave 4):                        │
│      For prefixes with 3–6 primes and marginal abundance (1.5 < σ/N < 2.05):  │
│      • Build a (k+1)×(k+2) integer lattice from scaled log-abundancies        │
│      • Log values computed at 256-bit MPFR precision × 2^200 → exact ℤ        │
│      • Run LLL basis reduction (exact rational Gram-Schmidt, δ = 3/4)          │
│      • If shortest vector's log-component exceeds tolerance 2^200/(2N),        │
│        no integer exponent combination can achieve σ(N)/N = 2+1/N → prune     │
│                                                                                 │
│   5. DYNAMIC MINIMUM FACTOR COUNT (UALBF-301, Prasad & Sunitha):              │
│      • Normal: QPN needs ≥ 7 distinct prime factors                            │
│      • If search cursor has passed primes 3 and 5 (both permanently excluded   │
│        from this branch): enforce ω(N) ≥ 15 (the Prasad-Sunitha bound for     │
│        gcd(N,15) = 1)                                                          │
│                                                                                 │
│   6. OVERFLOW KILL: If running abundancy σ(N_L)/N_L > 2.000001 → prune        │
│      (already overshooting; cannot achieve σ(N)/N = 2 + 1/N exactly)           │
│                                                                                 │
│   7. ABUNDANCE STARVATION (A1):                                                │
│      current_abundancy × suffix_abundance[last_idx] < 2.0 → prune             │
│      (not enough "abundance budget" remaining to reach target).                 │
│      When triggered, learn a starvation conflict clause via Z3 CDCL.           │
│                                                                                 │
│   8. COMPONENT EXHAUSTION (A3):                                                │
│      If fewer components remain than needed to reach min_prime_factors → prune │
│                                                                                 │
│   9. YAMADA STARVATION (at stop threshold):                                     │
│      Compute max tail abundancy from the largest prime in the prefix.           │
│      If current_abundancy × max_tail < 2.0 → prune (Yamada's underflow bound) │
│                                                                                 │
│  10. RAY-CASTING (Phase 4 — fused):                                            │
│      When N_L > 10^11, solve the QPN equation for candidate z = √(N_R):       │
│        a) Compute a = -2·N_L (mod σ(N_L))                                      │
│        b) Find modular inverse x_L = a⁻¹ (mod σ(N_L)) via Lean FFI            │
│        c) Solve z ≡ x_L (mod σ(N_L)) using composite Tonelli-Shanks (CRT)     │
│        d) For each root r_i and coefficient c:  z = r_i + c · σ(N_L)          │
│        e) SIEVE: reject z with illegal p-adic valuations (precomputed)         │
│        f) COPRIMALITY: reject z sharing a prime factor with N_L                │
│        g) SIZE CHECK: N = N_L · z² must satisfy target_min < N < target_max    │
│        h) σ CONSISTENCY: factor z, compute σ(z²), verify = required value      │
│        i) If σ(z²) == required_s_r → QUASIPERFECT NUMBER FOUND (exit 0)       │
│                                                                                 │
│ RESULTS:                                                                        │
│   No quasiperfect number found in any tested prefix — all candidates pruned.   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

